    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_576319395" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/576319395" />
    <a title="Jen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6049062-jen"><img alt="Jen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1460575899p2/6049062.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/576319395?book_show_action=true">Mar 31, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jen" href="/user/show/6049062-jen">Jen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781101602188" href="/book/show/17703290-the-king">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=kindle-own">kindle-own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=vampires">vampires</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=damaged-hero-heroine">damaged-hero-heroine</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=paranormal-romance">paranormal-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=april-reads">april-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6049062-jen?shelf=buddy-read-with-books-n-buddies">buddy-read-with-books-n-buddies</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer576319395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1786286643914949436">Where to begin with this one?? For starters, I will say that I was so looking forward to this book. I swear that once a year just is not enough for the BDB series. I was nervous about this book because my expectations were through the roof, and whenever I have high expectations; I am usually let down in some way. Unfortunately, in some ways I was let down; however the story certainly wasn&apos;t drastically bad. My biggest complaint was that I just didn&apos;t get enough of my wonderful origional brothers</span>
  <span id="freeText1786286643914949436" style="display:none">Where to begin with this one?? For starters, I will say that I was so looking forward to this book. I swear that once a year just is not enough for the BDB series. I was nervous about this book because my expectations were through the roof, and whenever I have high expectations; I am usually let down in some way. Unfortunately, in some ways I was let down; however the story certainly wasn't drastically bad. My biggest complaint was that I just didn't get enough of my wonderful origional brothers. In fact, most of this book was about couples that haven't been a part of the BDB clan from the beginning. This really disappointed me, as I was expecting that everything was going to come full circle, and there would be some closure on some major issues that have been stewing since very close to the beginning. <br /><br />In Book #12, we get the storyline for not only Wrath and Beth, but of the past King and Queen. This is Wrath's mom and dad, and we get flashbacks that fill in some blanks about their history and how they met. At first it is confusing about who JR Ward is writing about; but once I figured out that it was Wrath's parents then I settled into learning a bit about their past. Considering that this book is called "The King," we don't get a very big storyline with Wrath and Beth. I felt somewhat cheated about that; but I will say that the parts with them were very emotional and intense. This made up for the fact that I didn't get to see them much. When the pages were about them, I was captivated, and I fully embraced the magic that has always surrounded this couple.<br /><br />As far as the rest of the book goes, it is about a few other couples. The problem for me was that some of these couples I was never emotionally attached to in the first place. This made it so that the parts in the story that were about these characters, often became boring and flat out frustrating. There was Sola and Assail, who I will admit did grow on me. Then there was Treyz and his Chosen Selena. Yes, Xcor and Layla were a part of this story; but surprisingly enough not near as much as I thought they would be. This leads me to my next thought about this book.<br /><br />I was under the impression that this was the last BDB book in the series, and then JR Ward was moving on to write about the BOB's? Without me revealing any spoilers all I can say regarding this is there was no HEA's for these couples. Things were left hanging, which means there must be another book coming out? <br /><br />So now we have another year to wait for answers that we were hoping to get in this book. Let's hope that when the next book comes out, our curiousity will be fulfilled and that it will be a book that will hold our attention! I miss the days of the first six BDB books. Those books held true magic between the covers, and I find that the newer installments don't have the same spark. I still enjoy Ms. Ward's humor and writing style, I just wish there was more of it and less chaos. All in all, she must be doing something right though, as I still wait each year until I can catch a glimpse of my favorite Brothers again. For some reason, for me it feels like I am coming back home to my own family...and I wouldn't have it any other way! </span>
  <a data-text-id="1786286643914949436" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


